==English==
===Etymology===
{{ME.}} ''amercen'' from Anglo-French ''amercy'' =  f. à, to, at + merci, from  {{L.}} [[mercedem]] ''[[wages]]'', [[renumeration]], a [[present]], a [[favour]]

===Transitive verb===
'''to amerce'''
#{{law}} to [[impose]] an [[arbitrary]] [[penalty]], especially such a [[fine]]
#:''But I'll '''amerce''' you with so strong a fine, that you shall all repent the loss of mine'' - Shakespeare, "Romeo and Juliet"
#(''figurative'') to punish, to make an exaction:
#: ''Thou shalt be amerced for sins unknown.'' - Byron, "Cain" 
# To fine a certain amount:
#:''The person, in whose house the conventicle met, was amerced a like sum.'' - Hume History of England, 1806
#''(before "of) "To deprive of:
#: ''Millions of spirits for his fault amerced Of Heaven'' - Milton, Paradise Lost

